#### L-5: Understanding Your Rights as a Tenant
*Strategy:* Decode + Assert
*See also:* Ho-4: Knowing Your Rights as a Renter or Homeowner (the practical side --- maintenance, deposits, inspections), L-1: Negotiating a Contract (for reading your lease), L-3: Writing a Demand Letter (if your landlord will not act)
*My Man Jeeves:* _One observes that the relationship between landlord and tenant is, in most American jurisdictions, governed by a rather comprehensive body of law that the landlord has read and the tenant has not. This is not, one might note, an oversight. The lease itself is the landlord's document, composed by the landlord's attorney, printed on the landlord's letterhead, and presented to the tenant at a moment of maximum vulnerability --- when one has already packed, hired movers, and informed one's current residence of departure. The implied warranty of habitability, the statutory limits on security deposits, the protections against retaliatory eviction --- these exist in every state, though they vary with a creativity that borders on the artistic. The difficulty is not that the tenant lacks rights. It is that exercising them requires knowing they exist, which the lease is under no obligation to mention. One's Agent has read your state's landlord-tenant statute. It is prepared to be specific._

*The Spec:*
::: prompt
I am a tenant and I need to understand my rights.
My state and city: [state, city]
My situation: [describe what's happening --- habitability
issue / security deposit dispute / lease renewal pressure /
possible eviction / landlord entering without notice /
retaliation after a complaint / other]
My lease type: [month-to-month / fixed-term, and when it
expires]
What my landlord has said or done: [specific actions,
communications, or threats]
What I've done so far: [nothing / complained verbally /
complained in writing / called code enforcement / other]
Please:
1. Tell me my specific rights under my state and local
   landlord-tenant law for this situation
2. Tell me what my landlord is and is not legally allowed
   to do
3. Identify whether anything my landlord has done may
   already be a violation
4. Give me the exact steps to protect myself, in order,
   starting with what I should do today
5. Draft any written notice I need to send
Give me the most conservative, legally accurate answer.
I will verify with a lawyer or legal aid if escalation
is needed.
:::
*What to do with the Output:* Document everything in writing from this point forward. If your Agent identifies a habitability violation, send written notice to your landlord --- certified mail, return receipt, keep a copy. Photograph the condition with a timestamp. If your Agent identifies potential retaliation, you now know the statute that protects you, and you can name it in your next communication. That specificity changes the conversation.

::: fairness
Eviction filings --- even those that are dismissed or ruled in the tenant's favor --- appear on background checks and can prevent a tenant from securing future housing for years. This means a landlord who files a retaliatory eviction and loses still wins: the tenant's record is marked. Some jurisdictions have begun sealing dismissed evictions, but most have not. Ask your Agent: _"In [state], do dismissed evictions appear on tenant screening reports, and what can I do about it?"_ The answer will inform whether you fight or negotiate.[^l5-1]
:::


::: tip
The single most protective thing a tenant can do is communicate in writing. Text messages count. Emails count. A handwritten note slid under the office door with a photo of it counts. Verbal complaints evaporate. Written complaints become evidence. Ask your Agent: _"Draft a written notice to my landlord about [issue] that establishes a paper trail and cites the relevant statute."_
:::


::: science
A 2023 Princeton Eviction Lab study found that in most American cities, the majority of tenants facing eviction never appear in court --- and of those who do, fewer than 10% have legal representation. Landlords are represented in over 80% of cases. The representation gap, more than the merits of any individual case, predicts the outcome. Legal aid organizations exist in every state. Your Agent can find the one in your jurisdiction.[^l5-2]
:::


<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED: State-by-state security deposit limits and return deadlines. Many states cap deposits at 1-2 months' rent and require return within 14-30 days with an itemized deduction list. Violations of these statutes often carry penalties of 2x or 3x the deposit amount — a fact most tenants do not know and most landlords count on them not knowing. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): The power asymmetry of the landlord-tenant relationship is not just informational — it is existential. The landlord risks a vacancy. The tenant risks homelessness. This asymmetry shapes every negotiation, every complaint, every decision about whether to assert a right or stay quiet. The fear of retaliation is rational, not neurotic. The entry should name this without pretending a spec template resolves it. -->

[^l5-1]: The National Housing Law Project ([nhlp.org](https://www.nhlp.org)) publishes resources on eviction record sealing and tenant screening reform by state.

[^l5-2]: Desmond, Matthew. _Evicted: Poverty and Profit in the American City._ Crown, 2016. See also the Princeton Eviction Lab ([evictionlab.org](https://evictionlab.org)) for current national eviction filing data.

